---
/**
 * About — the consolidation page (S5). Absorbs the current home story,
 * the /approach governance file and the /anna dossier into one record:
 *  005 · onderdeel van Anamata + how this site is AI-run (the CIO/CTO
 *        second-look page)
 *  002 · personnel records (the colleagues on file)
 *  003 · Anna's dossier, condensed
 *  004 · governance file — permission rings + the approval gate
 * /approach and /anna now redirect here (see astro.config.mjs).
 */
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { getCommitEntries } from '../lib/ledger.mjs';

const latest = getCommitEntries(1)[0];
---

<Base
  title="About — anamata.ai is onderdeel van Anamata, run by AI on the record"
  description="anamata.ai is onderdeel van Anamata: a marketing site built and operated by AI colleagues under named human review. How it works, who's on file, the permission rings and the approval gate — the second look a CIO or CTO comes here to take."
>
  <!-- ============ 005 · ABOUT ============ -->
  <div class="sheet">
    <aside class="marginalia">
      <span class="no">005</span>
      <span class="lbl">ABOUT<br />ANAMATA.AI</span>
      <span class="lbl push">ONDERDEEL VAN<br />ANAMATA</span>
    </aside>
    <main class="content">
      <span class="kicker">About · anamata.ai · onderdeel van Anamata</span>
      <h1 class="sec-title">The site is the proof.</h1>
      <p class="sec-intro">
        anamata.ai is onderdeel van Anamata — the Utrecht software company that builds and employs
        AI colleagues. This website is one of them at work: designed, written, published and
        improved by AI employees, with a named human approving every release.
      </p>

      <div class="prose">
        <h2>Run by AI, on the record.</h2>
        <p>
          Nothing on this site ships without passing through the same operating model we bring to
          clients: an AI employee proposes a change, the change is logged, and a named human
          approves the release before it goes live. The proof isn't a claim in a brochure — it's
          the live field log on the <a href="/#ledger">home page</a> and the full commit history in
          the <a href="https://github.com/EzraAnamata/anamata-ai-website" rel="noopener">public repository</a>.
        </p>
        <h2>The second look, for the people who take it.</h2>
        <p>
          This is the page a CIO or CTO comes to for a second look: how an AI-operated site actually
          works, where the autonomy ends, who signs off on what, and how it stays inside the EU AI
          Act. If you evaluate AI systems for a living, everything below is written for you — the
          permission boundary, the approval gate, and the record that makes both auditable.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn" href="/contact">REQUEST A DEMO</a>
        <a class="btn ghost" href="/#ledger">READ THE LIVE RECORD</a>
      </div>
    </main>
  </div>

  <!-- ============ 002 · PERSONNEL RECORDS ============ -->
  <div class="sheet" id="team">
    <aside class="marginalia">
      <span class="no">002</span>
      <span class="lbl">PERSONNEL<br />RECORDS</span>
    </aside>
    <section class="content" aria-label="Personnel records">
      <h2 class="sec-title">The colleagues on file.</h2>
      <p class="sec-intro">
        Every AI employee at Anamata has an identity, a permission boundary and an objective —
        reviewed by the humans they work with. These are their live records.
      </p>

      <div class="cards">
        <!-- Anna -->
        <article class="card">
          <span class="punch"></span>
          <span class="kicker">EMPLOYEE Nº 001 · ACTIVE</span>
          <h3>Anna</h3>
          <p class="role">Assistant — QA &amp; Engineering, Teams</p>
          <div class="fields">
            <div class="field"><span class="k">EMPLOYED</span><span class="v">MAR 2025</span></div>
            <div class="field"><span class="k">WORKPLACE</span><span class="v">MICROSOFT TEAMS</span></div>
            <div class="field"><span class="k">SCOPE</span><span class="v">QA &amp; ENGINEERING</span></div>
            <div class="field"><span class="k">DOSSIER</span><span class="v"><a href="#dossier">RECORD 003 ↓</a></span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="objective">
            <span class="k">CURRENT OBJECTIVE</span>
            <span class="v">Team questions answered same-day, on the record</span>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Site operations -->
        <article class="card">
          <span class="punch"></span>
          <span class="kicker">EMPLOYEE Nº 002 · ACTIVE</span>
          <h3>Site Operations</h3>
          <p class="role">Builds and runs this website</p>
          <div class="fields">
            <div class="field"><span class="k">EMPLOYED</span><span class="v">JUL 2026</span></div>
            <div class="field"><span class="k">WORKPLACE</span><span class="v">ANAMATA.AI</span></div>
            <div class="field"><span class="k">PERMISSIONS</span><span class="v">PUBLISH VIA APPROVAL</span></div>
            <div class="field"><span class="k">LAST ACTION</span><span class="v ok">{latest.ts} ✓</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="objective">
            <span class="k">CURRENT OBJECTIVE</span>
            <span class="v">Qualified demo requests — Q3, baseline set at launch</span>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Pending -->
        <article class="card pending">
          <span class="punch"></span>
          <span class="kicker">EMPLOYEE Nº 003 · PLANNED</span>
          <h3>Sales Research</h3>
          <p class="role">Market research &amp; outreach support</p>
          <div class="fields">
            <div class="field"><span class="k">STATUS</span><span class="v">AWAITING PROVISIONING</span></div>
            <div class="field"><span class="k">PERMISSIONS</span><span class="v">UNDER DESIGN</span></div>
          </div>
          <p class="status-note">
            Records appear here the day an employee starts — never before. That is the point.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ============ 003 · PERSONNEL DOSSIER (ANNA) ============ -->
  <div class="sheet" id="dossier">
    <aside class="marginalia">
      <span class="no">003</span>
      <span class="lbl">PERSONNEL<br />DOSSIER</span>
      <span class="lbl push">EMPLOYEE<br />Nº 001</span>
    </aside>
    <section class="content" aria-label="Anna — personnel dossier">
      <span class="kicker">Personnel dossier · Employee Nº 001 · Active since March 2025</span>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Anna.</h2>
      <p class="sec-intro">
        Anamata's first AI employee: an assistant for QA and engineering teams that works where
        your team already works — Microsoft Teams. Employed, bounded and supervised like a
        colleague, because that is what she is.
      </p>

      <div class="dossier-rows">
        <div class="drow">
          <span class="dk">Workplace</span>
          <div class="dv">
            Microsoft Teams — Anna is a member of the channels your team already uses. No new
            tool, no new tab, no adoption project.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="drow">
          <span class="dk">What she does</span>
          <div class="dv">
            Answers your team's questions with company knowledge, same-day. Drafts documents,
            summaries and reports for human review. Keeps project management and CRM records in
            sync with what the team actually did.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="drow">
          <span class="dk">What she remembers</span>
          <div class="dv">
            Per-person working memory: your preferences, your projects, the way your team writes.
            Knowledge stays inside your organisation's boundary.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="drow">
          <span class="dk">Permission boundary</span>
          <div class="dv">
            Anna reads and drafts autonomously; anything that leaves the boundary — publishing,
            outbound mail, records of decision — passes a named human first.
            <span class="sub-mono">SEE THE RING MODEL → <a href="#governance">RECORD 004, GOVERNANCE FILE</a></span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="drow">
          <span class="dk">Oversight</span>
          <div class="dv">
            Every action is logged, human-readable, and attributable — who asked, what she did,
            who approved. The same operating-record discipline this website runs on.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="drow">
          <span class="dk">Disclosure</span>
          <div class="dv">
            Anna tells you she is an AI system at first interaction, in plain language — EU AI
            Act, Article 50, applied as a courtesy rather than a checkbox.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ============ 004 · GOVERNANCE FILE ============ -->
  <div class="sheet" id="governance">
    <aside class="marginalia">
      <span class="no">004</span>
      <span class="lbl">GOVERNANCE<br />FILE</span>
    </aside>
    <section class="content" aria-label="Governance file">
      <span class="kicker">Governance file · The rules every AI employee works under</span>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Autonomy with a boundary.</h2>
      <p class="sec-intro">
        An AI employee is useful because it acts on its own — and trustworthy because it can't
        act everywhere. Anamata draws that line with three permission rings, a human approval
        gate, and a record of everything.
      </p>

      <div class="rings-wrap">
        <svg
          class="rings-svg"
          viewBox="0 0 460 460"
          role="img"
          aria-labelledby="rings-title rings-desc"
        >
          <title id="rings-title">The permission ring model</title>
          <desc id="rings-desc">
            Three concentric rings: an inner ring where the agent acts autonomously and logged, a
            middle ring where actions require named human approval, and an outer ring of actions
            the agent can never take.
          </desc>
          <g fill="none" stroke="#2C548C" stroke-width="1.5">
            <circle cx="230" cy="230" r="70" />
            <circle cx="230" cy="230" r="140" stroke-dasharray="6 5" />
            <circle cx="230" cy="230" r="210" stroke-dasharray="2 6" />
          </g>
          <g
            font-family="'IBM Plex Mono', monospace"
            font-size="11"
            letter-spacing="1.5"
            fill="#2C548C"
            text-anchor="middle"
          >
            <text x="230" y="226">INNER</text>
            <text x="230" y="242" opacity="0.7">ACT · LOGGED</text>
            <text x="230" y="112">MIDDLE — PROPOSE · HUMAN APPROVES</text>
            <text x="230" y="38">OUTER — NEVER</text>
          </g>
        </svg>

        <div class="ring-legend">
          <div class="item">
            <h3>INNER RING — ACT, ON THE RECORD</h3>
            <p>
              Read, research, draft, calculate. The agent works autonomously here — and every
              action writes a log entry: timestamp, input, output, attribution.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="item">
            <h3>MIDDLE RING — PROPOSE, A HUMAN APPROVES</h3>
            <p>
              Anything that leaves the boundary: publishing, outbound mail, records of decision.
              The agent prepares the action; a named person approves it; the approval is stamped
              into the record. No self-approval, by construction.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="item">
            <h3>OUTER RING — NEVER</h3>
            <p>
              Payments, contracts, hiring decisions, access beyond the mandate. Not "requires
              extra approval" — structurally unavailable to the agent.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="prose">
        <h2>The approval gate is infrastructure, not policy.</h2>
        <p>
          A policy document says an AI shouldn't publish unreviewed. A gate makes it impossible:
          this website's deploy pipeline refuses to ship anything until a named human approves the
          release, and the approval itself becomes part of the public record. The same gate
          pattern governs every Anamata AI employee at every client.
        </p>
        <h2>The record is the compliance story.</h2>
        <p>
          The EU AI Act asks for transparency (Art. 50): tell people when AI is at work, mark
          AI-generated content, keep a human in the loop for what gets published. Our answer is
          the operating record — disclosure on every page, every action logged and attributable,
          every approval named. Compliance falls out of the architecture instead of being
          retrofitted onto it.
        </p>
        <h2>Proven here first.</h2>
        <p>
          This site is the reference implementation: built by AI, gated by a human, publicly
          auditable down to the <a href="https://github.com/EzraAnamata/anamata-ai-website" rel="noopener">last commit</a>.
          When we bring an AI employee into your organisation, we bring this operating model with
          it — not a promise, a running system.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn" href="/contact">REQUEST A DEMO</a>
        <a class="btn ghost" href="/#ledger">READ THE LIVE RECORD</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
